{"filePath":"/home/vic/microsoldering-notes/topics/01-embedded-controller-intro.tex","newString":"The U300 has 128 pins. Here are the most critical ones for understanding power management:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \pin{46}{KBC\_PWR\_ON} - Enables the P3V3A power rail
    \item \pin{57}{SLP\_S3\#} - Sleep state indicator (S3 = Suspend to RAM)
    \item \pin{52}{SLP\_S4\#} - Sleep state indicator (S4 = Hibernate)
    \item \pin{86}{ADP\_PRES\_OUT} - Adapter presence detection
    \item \pin{1}{VCC1\_POR\#\_3} - Power-on reset
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\linewidth]{output/page46_full.png}
\caption{Full view of schematic page 46 showing U300 with key pins labeled. Pin 46 (KBC\_PWR\_ON) is on the right side, pins 52 and 57 (sleep states) are on the top edge.}
\label{fig:u300-pins}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:u300-pins} shows the complete U300 schematic. For troubleshooting:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Check pin 46 voltage when system won't power on
    \item Monitor pins 52/57 during sleep/wake transitions
    \item Verify pin 86 when adapter detection fails
\end{itemize}","oldStrin...

